    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The chaos you're seeing is typical for a crisis, but you can cut through the noise by focusing on specific high-priority targets. First, head straight to the airline's dedicated \"customer care\" or \"re-accommodation\" desk rather than the general lines, as they are the only ones authorized to issue rebooking vouchers immediately. If those lines are also backed up, look for the airport's own \"re-accommodation\" counter, which often has a faster queue for passengers whose flights were cancelled by the carrier.\n\nTo manage the crowd, try to move quickly through the terminal using the \"Fast Track\" or \"Priority\" lanes if your ticket allows you to use them for rebooking. If you don't have priority access, avoid the main concourse crowds and stick to the service desk area where the action is concentrated; this minimizes the time spent wandering aimlessly. Remember that in a crisis, the staff are overwhelmed but focused on their specific tasks, so speaking clearly and politely to the front of the line is often more effective than waiting for a general announcement.\n\nAlso, consider asking a fellow traveler or a staff member if there's a specific \"fast lane\" for re-accommodation that isn't widely known,",
